        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        De Pompeij rebus gestis tam magnificè Liuius, vt ab ipso Augusto audiret, Pompeianus. At Lucanus Pompeio quantò 
                        liberalior: Ca[e]sari iniquior? Plinius, vtriq[ue] a[e]quus; et Plutarchus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                <person name="Pompey"/>
                <person name="Augustus"/>
                <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                <person name="Lucan"/>
                <person name="Pliny the Elder"/>
                <person name="Plutarch"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Livy wrote so proudly of Pompey's achievements, that he was called ‘Pompeianus’ by Augustus himself. But how much more generous to Pompey and 
                harsh on Caesar was Lucan! Pliny was fair to both, as was Plutarch.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        { Huc Pompeij grauis prouincia de tot Romanorum corruptis legibus, moribusq[ue] corrigendis: apud C[ornelium] Tacitum, Annalium l. 3. 
                        Locus est subtili disquisitione dignus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Pompey"/>
                    <person name="Tacitus"/>
                    <book title="The Annals"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                On this point Pompey’s serious task of reforming a great many corrupt laws and customs of the Romans, see Tacitus, bk. 3 of the Annals. 
                This is a place that is worth meticulous scrutiny. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>Dua[e] Ca[e]saris decades: quales vna Scipionis;</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>altera Sylla[e], s[upr]a. Nam extraordinaria[e] Virtutis, fortuna[e]q[ue] Triumviri, Scipio, Sylla, Ca[e]sar. 
                        Et Ca[e]sar, plus quàm illi ambo. Omnes in Ca[e]sare manes: etiam ( aduersa[e] factionis vox.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Sulla"/>
                    <X-ref book_title="Pharsalia" language="LA" person="Lucan" text="Omnes in Ca[e]sare manes"/>
                    <internal_ref text="s[upr]a">
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000246" text="[224]"/>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000299" text="[277]"/>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000426" text="[404]"/>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000859" text="[AAA5[r]]"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The two decades of Caesar; similar first to the one of Scipio and then to that of Sulla, [see] above. For the triumvirs Scipio, 
                Sulla, and Caesar were of outstanding virtue and fortune. Caesar even more than both of the former. 
                "All the ghosts of the dead are in Caesar," even the voice of the opposing party.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
